  "prompt": "Who are Hindu Gods?",
  "response": "Hinduism encompasses a vast array of deities, beliefs, and practices. Some of the principal Hindu gods and goddesses include:\n\n1. **Brahma**: The creator god, often depicted with four heads representing the four Vedas (sacred texts) and aspects of creation.\n\n2. **Vishnu**: The preserver and protector of the universe, known for his ten avatars (incarnations), including Rama and Krishna. Vishnu is often depicted resting on the serpent Ananta.\n\n3. **Shiva**: The destroyer and transformer, Shiva represents the cyclical nature of creation and destruction. He is often depicted as a yogi and is associated with the lingam symbol.\n\n4. **Saraswati**: The goddess of knowledge, music, art, and wisdom, often depicted with a veena (musical instrument) and a swan.\n\n5. **Lakshmi**: The goddess of wealth, fortune, and prosperity, often depicted sitting or standing on a lotus and holding gold coins.\n\n6. **Parvati**: The goddess of love, fertility, and devotion, Parvati is the consort of Shiva and is associated with various forms, including Durga and Kali.\n\n7. **Ganesha**: The elephant-headed god, known as the remover of obstacles and the god of beginnings. He is worshiped before starting any new venture.\n\n8. **Hanuman**: The monkey god and devotee of Lord Rama, known for his immense strength and devotion. He symbolizes loyalty and devotion.\n\n9. **Rama**: An avatar of Vishnu and the hero of the epic Ramayana, Rama embodies dharma (righteousness) and virtue.\n\n10. **Krishna**: Another avatar of Vishnu, Krishna is known for his playful and mischievous nature, as well as his teachings in the Bhagavad Gita.\n\n11. **Durga**: A powerful goddess who represents the divine feminine force and is worshipped for her strength and ability to overcome evil.\n\n12. **Kali**: The fierce aspect of the goddess Durga, Kali represents time, change, and destruction of evil forces, often depicted with a fierce expression and a necklace of skulls.\n\nThese deities are often worshiped in various forms, with rituals, festivals, and stories that celebrate their attributes and teachings. Hinduism is also characterized by a belief in many other local deities and regional variations in worship.",
